## Assessment Readiness Package

Before the assessor begins work, the ISSO prepares a formal assessment readiness package — a structured set of documents that enables the assessor to plan their work efficiently and understand the system before testing begins.

**Assessment readiness package contents:**

*System overview documentation:*
- Current SSP (Task I-2 version) with revision history
- System description and architecture diagrams
- Asset inventory with component roles
- Data flow diagrams showing ePHI flows
- System boundary documentation

*Control implementation evidence:*
- Assessment package organized by control family (Sections 1-15 as referenced in SSP evidence citations)
- Each section contains the specific evidence referenced in the as-implemented SSP entries
- Evidence index mapping each control to its section

*Supporting documentation:*
- POA&M with current status and compensating controls documentation
- Risk register (Days 37-38) providing context for the prioritization of findings
- Continuous monitoring strategy (Day 52) showing ongoing monitoring capabilities
- Most recent monitoring records (GuardDuty findings, Config compliance, vulnerability scan results, restoration test)

*Access logistics:*
- Read-only AWS console access for the assessor (IAM role with read-only permissions — assessor should not have write access to the production environment)
- OpenMRS test environment access for application testing (not the production system — a production-equivalent test instance)
- Contact list for interview scheduling: ISSO, IT Administrator, Health IT Manager, Compliance Officer, System Owner
- Assessment schedule with defined windows for technical testing

*Rules of engagement:*
- Scope: defined system boundary (matching SSP boundary)
- No active exploitation testing against the production environment — testing uses the test instance
- Findings are communicated to the ISSO before the final report for factual accuracy verification (not to change findings, but to correct factual errors)
- Sensitive information handling — NDA in place before any access is granted

