## What I Am Still Thinking About

One practical question from today's work: how should the ISSO handle the assessor's access to the production OpenMRS environment?

The assessment methodology requires the assessor to test implemented controls — not just review documents. For some controls, testing requires access to the actual production system: verifying that MFA is enforced requires attempting to authenticate without MFA. Verifying that session timeout is configured requires testing the timeout behavior. Verifying that audit logging captures required fields requires generating events and reviewing the resulting log entries.

But production systems in healthcare environments contain live patient data. Granting an external assessor access to a production EHR — even read-only access — creates a disclosure risk for ePHI. The assessor does not need to view actual patient records to test most controls.

The approach I want to document: the assessor tests application-level controls in a production-equivalent test environment — the same software version, same configuration, same role definitions, but populated with synthetic test data rather than real patient data. Infrastructure-level controls (AWS configuration, IAM policies, security group rules, CloudTrail) are tested against the production AWS environment using a read-only IAM role that provides console access without data access.

This approach separates the infrastructure assessment (production, read-only) from the application assessment (test environment, equivalent configuration) in a way that enables thorough testing without creating unnecessary ePHI exposure. The rules of engagement document should specify this approach explicitly so the assessor and MyClinic agree on the access model before the engagement begins.

